:content
Reload the page. Up to 2 arguments.<ul>
<li>Argument 1&#58; the text to show on the link.
<li>Argument 2 (optional)&#58; the position to go (anchor).
</ul>
<p>
Reloading a page is interesting when it contains 

!read primitives.phtml 1, link, def, random variables 
. In this case, to each reloading, the resulting
page is different.
<p>

!set tmp0=!randint 1, 1000

!set m_nn=$[rint($(tmp0))]

For example, in this page we have defined the variable <tt>\nn</tt>
to be a random integer between 1 and 1000, by the command
<tt>\def{integer nn=random(1..1000)}</tt>. Here is its current value&#58;
<p><center><tt>\nn</tt>=$m_nn.</center><p>
Now 

!read primitives.phtml 2, reload, reload the page, reload 
 (<tt>\reload{reload the page}</tt>)
to see the value of <tt>\nn</tt> change.
<small>(The button ``reload'' of the browser will not produce this effect.)</small>
<p>
